      	<div type="translation" xml:lang="eng" resp="part:emfr">
      		<p rend="stanza" n="1">
      			May Rājasiṃha <supplied reason="explanation">the lion among kings</supplied> Raṇajaya <supplied reason="explanation">the victorious among kings</supplied> Śrībhara <supplied reason="explanation">the Fortune-bearer</supplied> Citrakarmuka <supplied reason="explanation">he whose quiver is a wonder</supplied> Ekavīra <supplied reason="explanation">the unique hero</supplied> Śivacūḍāmaṇi <supplied reason="explanation">he who has Śiva as diadem</supplied> protect the earth for long.
      		</p>
      	</div>
      	
      	<div type="translation" xml:lang="fra" resp="part:sybr"><!--add second translator:  part:emfr"-->
      		<lg>
      			<l>Puisse Rājasiṃha, le vainqueur au combat,</l>
      			<l>Celui qui apporte la prospérité, celui qui possède un arc resplendissant,</l>
      			<l>Le héros unique, longtemps protéger la terre,</l>
      			<l>Lui qui porte Śiva comme diadème !</l>
      		</lg>
      	</div>
      	
      	<div type="commentary">
      		<p>The same verse is found in two other inscriptions of Narasiṃhavarman II. See tfaPallava054, stanza 12 and tfaPallava060, stanza 3.<!--Update cross-ref!--></p>
      	</div>
      	
